t 3: Grassroot initiatives -- t13 Social media and the use of technology in home language maintenance -- t14 Transnational grassroots language planning in the era of mobility and the Internet -- t15 Community language schools -- t16 The drivers of home language maintenance and development in indigenous communities -- tPart 4: The role of society -- tTopic area 4.1: Social justice and inclusiveness -- t17 Language policy and planning for language maintenance: The macro and meso levels -- t18 Language attitudes and ideologies on linguistic diversity -- t19 Social justice and inclusiveness through linguistic human rights in education -- t20 Disabilities and home language maintenance: Myths, models of disability, and equity -- tTopic area 4.2: Formal education -- t21 Models of formal education and minority language teaching across countries -- t22 Teachers’ beliefs and attitudes towards home languages maintenance and their effects -- t23 The mainstream classroom and home language maintenance -- tAbout the contributors -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index -- tLanguage Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEven a cursory look at conference programs and proceedings reveals a burgeoning interest in the field of social and affective factors in home language maintenance and development. To date, however, research on this topic has been published in piecemeal fashion, subsumed under the more general umbrella of ‘bilingualism’. Within bilingualism research, there has been an extensive exploration of linguistic and psycholinguistic perspectives on the one hand, and educational practices and outcomes on the other. In comparison, social and affective factors – which lead people to either maintain or shift the language – have been under-researched. This is the first volume that brings together the different strands in research on social and affective factors in home language maintenance and development, ranging from the micro-level (family language policies and practices), to the meso-level (community initiatives) and the macro-level (mainstream educational policies and their implementation). The volume showcases a wide distribution across contexts and populations explored. Contributors from around the world represent different research paradigms and perspectives, providing a rounded overview of the state-of-the-art in this flourishing field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aHeritage language speakers. 0aLanguage maintenance. 0aLanguages in contact. 0aNative languagexStudy and teaching. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aBilingualism.  aLanguage Management.  aLanguage Policies.  aMultilingualism.  aSocial and Affective Factors.1 aAlbury, Nathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnnamalai, E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCamacho, José, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheatham, Gregory A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Houwer, Annick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEisenchlas, Susana A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEisenchlas, Susana A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHatoss, Anikó, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuang, Jing, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJuvonen, Päivi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnapp, Karlfried, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLan Curdt-Christiansen, Xiao, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLanza, Eliz